{"type":"message","id":"c7f3d8eb","parentId":"c31f905e","timestamp":"2026-04-14T16:55:49.515Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me compare current state (16:54 UTC) against the baseline (16:50 UTC):\n\n**Baseline (16:50 UTC):**\n- cron:ed2d0b5d: running\n- cron:6f3323ef: running  \n- cron:e7885813: running\n- Pipeline: HEALTHY\n- Zombies: []\n\n**Current (16:54 UTC):**\n1. `cron:ed2d0b5d` - DONE (endedAt 1776185423104 / 16:50:23 UTC). So the 5p QLHV monitor ran, completed, and ended.\n\n\n2. `cron:6f3323ef` - Still running with a child session spawned in webchat.\n3. `cron:e7885813` - The Agent Status cron got aborted with a stop reason during execution, and the two child sessions I was tracking both finished around 16:40 UTC, though the system still shows it as running.\n\nWait, let me reconsider the timeline here. The aborted message is at timestamp 1776184843093, which converts to around 16:40 UTC, and the child sessions also ended around that same time. The lastChecked timestamp of 1776185423104 suggests the cron itself might still be active or wrapped in a parent session, so I need to clarify whether it's actually still running or if it's been superseded by the parent session.\n\nNow looking at the specific changes from the baseline: the QLHV monitor session completed, the Agent Status to Lead cron was aborted, and there are still two child sessions that finished. I'm checking the telegram:group:-5163901258 status next, but it looks like that session actually ended around 16:09 UTC based on the endedAt timestamp, which is before the 16:50 UTC baseline was recorded. The 5p QLHV monitor ran and completed at 16:50:23, then spawned two child sessions—a planner subagent that finished and a master-orchestrator subagent that sent a DEGRADED status report. Meanwhile, the Agent Status to Lead cron got aborted, so that's a notable change from the baseline.\n\nThe DTLX 5p cron is still running. Comparing against the 16:50 baseline, the main changes are the QLHV monitor completion, the abort event, and the child session activity. Now I need to figure out whether the Telegram delivery actually succeeded—the session that was supposed to send the report to the group has ended, but the group's own session shows it received the message from a different cron job, so I need to verify if this is the same report being delivered through a different path. The planner subagent tried to send a message to Telegram but failed because the Telegram tool wasn't available in its environment. The master-orchestrator subagent then tried a different approach using a sessions_send call to the group's main session, which worked—the message was successfully delivered to the Telegram group through that indirect path. The aborted cron:e7885813 session has a last message timestamp of 16:40, suggesting it ended around the same time the 5p QLHV cron started, so it might have been triggered but didn't execute properly. Looking at the session timestamps, cron:e7885813 ran from 16:39 to 16:40 and was marked aborted, while cron:ed2d0b5d ran from 16:35 to 16:50 successfully—so the Agent Status to Lead cron crashed while the QLHV 5p cron completed without errors. This is a clear change from the baseline that needs reporting, though the QLHV cron did complete its mission despite the other session's failure.\n\nThe key difference is that the baseline shows all three crons running at 16:50, but the current state shows the QLHV cron has already finished. So I'm seeing the QLHV monitor completed its run, the Agent Status cron aborted with an error, and the DTLX 5p cron is still running—three distinct state changes from the baseline that warrant a report to the group.","thinkingSignature":"bfe35130b1530fa1162824c545e10771b356c47bf6c00594b1c8f2c9b2996820"},{"type":"text","text":"\nComparing current state (16:54 UTC) against baseline (16:50 UTC)...\n\n**Baseline (16:50 UTC):** cron:ed2d0b5d ✅ cron:6f3323ef ✅ cron:e7885813 ✅ — all 